        <h1>Frequently Asked Questions</h1>
        <hr>

        <h3>What should be on backend side?</h3>
        <p>X-editable has no limitation to backend side, you can write it on any server language you prefer.<br>
        The common logic is: </p>
        <ol>
         <li>read <code>pk</code>, <code>name</code> and <code>value</code> from request (POST by default).</li>
         <li>apply validation of value. If validation failed - return HTTP status != 200 and error message in response body.</li>
         <li>If validation succeed - update object in database: set column specified by <code>name</code> to <code>value</code> using <code>pk</code> as object's unique identifier (<strong>ID</strong>).</li>
         <li>send HTTP 200 OK response.</li>
        </ol>
        <hr>

        <h3>Data is not submitted to server! Why?</h3>
        <p>The most possible reason is that you have empty <code>pk</code> or <code>url</code> options.<br> 
        If you want to submit data without pk please set <code>send</code> option to <code>"always"</code>.   
        </p>
        <p>Also form is not submitted if you did not change value. To manage this behavior see <code>savenochange</code> option.</p>
        <hr>

        <h3>How to change POST variables before submit?</h3>
        <p>You should use <code>params</code> option defined as a function:</p> 
        <pre>
$('#field').editable({
  ...        
  params: function(params) {
    var data = {};
    data['id'] = params.pk;
    data[params.name] = params.value;
    return data;
  }
}); 
</pre>
        <hr>
        
        <h3>How to submit stringified JSON?</h3>
        <p>You should use <code>params</code> option defined as a function:</p> 
        <pre>
//submit in JSON format        
$('#field').editable({
  ...        
  params: function(params) {
    return JSON.stringify(params);  //note: for older browsers you may need json2.js from json.org
  }
});  
</pre>
